  ],
  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "5ef65223-0bfe-4486-82a2-3469fa2d560c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Pre-Assessment"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5ef65223-0bfe-4486-82a2-3469fa2d560c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "55d48c0a-fa7d-4a4a-8aeb-fb99bc4de9d9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b50f59a8-1ad4-4336-af7c-2f61b0e41dd4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students in pairs or groups of three and read aloud the sentence on the board. Have students take turns one-by-one building on the conversation by starting their next sentence with \"Yes, and..\"",
        "name": "Yes, and...",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "For example:\n- **Opening Statement:** \"A mysterious talking cat started showing up to math class.\"\n- **Student 1:** \"Yes, and he said his name is Whiskers.\"\n- **Student 2:** \"Yes, and he happens to be very good at multiplication.\"\n- **Student 1:** \"Yes, and he has a sister who started showing up to English class.\"\n- **Student 2:** \"Yes, and he has a sister who started showing up to English class.\"\n\n(Optional) If you have time to play multiple rounds of the game, here are some additional opening statements:\n- \"The class down the hall just discovered a hidden tunnel beneath the school.\"\n- \"The principal announced that prom will be held on a spaceship this year.\"\n- \"Every locker in the main hallway suddenly started playing music.\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b50f59a8-1ad4-4336-af7c-2f61b0e41dd4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "66081255-07e7-40e7-824f-8c6665eab470"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "832e7c72-d889-48e0-baf8-cae976515fb7",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "832e7c72-d889-48e0-baf8-cae976515fb7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "66081255-07e7-40e7-824f-8c6665eab470"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3d771ce7-c39c-4ceb-9e6b-e3548f8e552e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Summarize the story you came up with. What were the last two sentences of your conversation?*\n- Have several groups summarize where their conversation went. Then have them share out their last sentence or two that they came up with.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that all groups started with the same sentence starter but may have ended up with very different conversations. Have students note any patterns between the stories as well as any differences. This game leads into the main activity by explaining how AI generates content.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3d771ce7-c39c-4ceb-9e6b-e3548f8e552e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "66081255-07e7-40e7-824f-8c6665eab470"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9f960284-44c1-415d-bad3-c48d0b39843d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Problem Solving with AI Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *artificial intelligence*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Predict the word that you think will probably come next in the following sentence: The dog barked at the...*\n- Ask students to predict the word that they think will probably come next (i.e. the most common word) and provide a reason for why they chose that word. Have all students raise their hand when they think of an answer. Start calling on students and have other students put down their hand if someone is called on who has the same answer.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students will see that there are several common possibilities that are chosen. Common words might include squirrel, mailman, stranger, etc. However, there will also be outliers that might not be as common (e.g. my aunt Lucy). Having students recognize that there are more and less common responses is a first step towards understanding how probability works while making this sort of prediction.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Model the AI Chat in Lesson 1, Level 1 for students.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "AI Predictions"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9f960284-44c1-415d-bad3-c48d0b39843d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d58e7d7-4ab5-49fc-99c5-06311246315a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Have students experiment with using the AI Chat to complete the sentence.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Have AI generate several outcomes to complete the sentence. You can keep prompting AI Chat using the same prompt or follow up by prompting it to \"generate three more answers\". You may also want to have students try out the prompt on their devices and compare responses."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d58e7d7-4ab5-49fc-99c5-06311246315a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "99209c13-8299-402c-9284-c999aee7ee6e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "99209c13-8299-402c-9284-c999aee7ee6e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "863c553c-8864-42b6-8843-938862feef34",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How does AI's output compare to the word you predicted?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should start to see how AI selects words based on probability. It tends to choose the most likely next word, which often mirrors our own prediction of the most-likely next word.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *probability*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read through this scenario of probability-driven predictions that make sense and are successful. Make sure students understand that the grey box represents the user input, and the blue box below represents the AI Chat response.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "863c553c-8864-42b6-8843-938862feef34",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9410008d-5598-4d64-bf0e-dc27bcb08c1b",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "AI uses the computational skill of pattern recognition to generate its most likely response. For example, it reads over thousands of sentences that contain the different phrases above (e.g. \"heard the knock at the…\") and starts to recognize a pattern.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9410008d-5598-4d64-bf0e-dc27bcb08c1b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "56a1eb78-f9cd-428e-b9ad-28d5cb5442bf",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Examine this scenario where probability-driven predictions fail because they don't rely on meaning.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Explain that AI focused on the words \"key\", \"on\", and \"table\" and abstracted away unnecessary details of the prompt.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "56a1eb78-f9cd-428e-b9ad-28d5cb5442bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "76f663ff-a258-462b-abca-8ec3d3263687",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Since AI doesn't understand meaning, it drew a single key resting on the table in an unrealistic way. It prioritized the literal meaning of the essential details of the sentence rather than considering the sentence as a whole.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "76f663ff-a258-462b-abca-8ec3d3263687",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d08ce653-939c-4854-8a91-705d97f5bf8c",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *abstraction*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d08ce653-939c-4854-8a91-705d97f5bf8c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fa75c521-ea40-446a-9af0-a65aad81eeac",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *prompt*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 2 to complete Levels 2 through 4.\n- **Level 2:** Students input \"Give me 3 gift ideas\" into AI Chat.\n- **Level 3:** Students input a more specific prompt that defines the person who is getting the gift.\n- **Level 4:** Students upload an image to accompany the specific prompt that they reuse from Level 3.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Prompting AI"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fa75c521-ea40-446a-9af0-a65aad81eeac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2e02f292-dea8-4be1-af07-8536cc7cda89",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the \"Plan a Perfect Trip with ChatGPT\" video.\n\n**Questions to consider with the video:**\nWhat tips might you give to someone else who is looking to improve their prompts?\n- What tips might you give to someone else who is looking to improve their prompts?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students might point out that they should include both information that they are interested in getting, but also information that they are not. They might also mention that including demographic information and specific numbers are helpful for more useful responses.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the\n\nVideos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Y-kGl_pc2afuSBKhKkdulu53X50mc7T-RQZA4vGLpY4/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2e02f292-dea8-4be1-af07-8536cc7cda89",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6496615d-0f51-47cc-98bb-6463ffa62ec3",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6496615d-0f51-47cc-98bb-6463ffa62ec3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8bebe965-525b-46ec-b79e-4c092ba5ff1f",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 5. Students choose one of the AI Chat levels that is configured for a specific task. They start by giving the AI Chat a generic prompt first (such as \"Help me plan a trip to Disney World\"), then make it more specific, then make it more specific and add an image. Students should update their prompt or interact with the AI Chat in at least three back and forth interactions.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This is a choice level, so students only need to complete one of the levels. However, if students finish early or are looking for an additional challenge, they can choose Option D: Debate an AI Partner level. This option is more challenging because it requires students to engage in a back-and-forth exchange with AI, refine their arguments, and adapt their reasoning based on AI's responses. Unlike other choices that focus on planning tasks, this level encourages students to critically analyze AI-generated arguments and practice constructing persuasive responses."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8bebe965-525b-46ec-b79e-4c092ba5ff1f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0d737803-884b-494c-b862-9628a65f04d1",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0d737803-884b-494c-b862-9628a65f04d1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e49694aa-2d0a-4504-9691-faabfd7aeea9",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 6 to complete the formative assessment. Display students' anonymous responses.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This level can be used as a formative assessment to check student understanding of the lesson objectives. Here are things to look for and actions you can take:\n- If students are only describing what happened rather than why it happened, prompt them to revisit earlier lesson segments on probability-driven outputs. Consider a quick group discussion where students share examples of prompts that worked well and why those prompts influenced AI's response.\n- If students seem uncertain about constructing high-quality prompts, have them re-examine Level 5 where best prompting strategies are summarized. They can also do a brief pair activity—each student provides a vague prompt, then a specific prompt, and compares the results.\n- If many students need more help, provide short demos or additional videos showing how multimodal inputs can change the AI's outputs. Or point them to the optional video about planning a family trip to emphasize how refining prompts improves results. Encourage a follow-up activity where students generate multiple answers to the same prompt, then analyze and explain what changed.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e49694aa-2d0a-4504-9691-faabfd7aeea9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "6df51da3-11fa-435a-a744-3cb4a9af986f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "92c894d9-dbcb-44f5-ab6f-80f2afe7da6e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students sit in a circle or small groups. Pose the Question of the Day to students. One by one, they quickly state their answer to the Question of the Day. Responses should be brief (one sentence or key phrase). They should see how many unique answers they can come up with.",
        "name": "Rapid Roundatable",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are struggling to answer the Question of the Day, have them think about which prompting strategies got them the most helpful AI Chat outputs. For example, ask students what details they included in their prompts or how they selected an image to add to their prompt."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "92c894d9-dbcb-44f5-ab6f-80f2afe7da6e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fd5332f7-c228-4a75-80c7-90b43704e991"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7eec985e-2bb2-402c-a9f8-e98361ff1c7e",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7eec985e-2bb2-402c-a9f8-e98361ff1c7e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fd5332f7-c228-4a75-80c7-90b43704e991"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2b13c1ff-0f4b-4ddd-b5ca-2329434ff2e1",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 7 to complete the End of Lesson Survey."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2b13c1ff-0f4b-4ddd-b5ca-2329434ff2e1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fd5332f7-c228-4a75-80c7-90b43704e991"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8a072b58-cd99-4e7e-838e-12a6a823595c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:**  Click through the animated slide to display the prompts:\n- *If a friend wanted to locate a certain bird in the wild, how would you help them? Would you give them . . .*\n- *a written description?*\n- *a picture?*\n- *a video?*\n- *an audio recording of its call?*\n- *something else?*\n- *Why?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that different types of media serve different purposes. Text provides details, images help with identification, and audio and video capture sound and movement. AI must process different inputs to generate useful responses.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to pick a media type, prompt them with follow up questions, such as: \"How do YOU recognize a bird in the wild?\" or \"Would text be enough to help a friend who has never seen this bird before?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8a072b58-cd99-4e7e-838e-12a6a823595c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f2c62f5-2d2c-43f2-a430-fef208bf79e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ee7be92e-569d-4ee1-9a19-3fc5125d8215",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ee7be92e-569d-4ee1-9a19-3fc5125d8215",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f2c62f5-2d2c-43f2-a430-fef208bf79e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "599ca8bc-1949-4a21-bbc3-5c02aeb72765",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "AI models like GPT-4, that powers ChatGPT, are trained to analyze multiple types of input (text, images, audio). Some AI models input text only, some input text and images, some input video, etc. Our AI Chat allows us to input text, images, and PDFs.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "599ca8bc-1949-4a21-bbc3-5c02aeb72765",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f2c62f5-2d2c-43f2-a430-fef208bf79e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6a4235d5-efc6-4b4a-8bb5-6c8a119f37bb",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *multimodal model*. Provide students with some real-world examples, such as Google Lens, self-driving cars, ChatGPT's image recognition, etc.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students ask about AI that uses all four types of input (text, image, video, and sound), acknowledge that some AI models specialize in one type while others combine them. Self-driving cars, for example, use vision and audio sensors."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6a4235d5-efc6-4b4a-8bb5-6c8a119f37bb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f2c62f5-2d2c-43f2-a430-fef208bf79e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e434066f-6641-4ef9-96fc-73404b85a4c9",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e434066f-6641-4ef9-96fc-73404b85a4c9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f2c62f5-2d2c-43f2-a430-fef208bf79e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d002e569-6df6-47ef-b40f-7c02831424ef",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Multimodal AI isn't just used in chatbots – it's changing industries.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d002e569-6df6-47ef-b40f-7c02831424ef",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f2c62f5-2d2c-43f2-a430-fef208bf79e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ab9cbb50-bf79-44c2-a6ea-268e5ea35f8d",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use the examples on the slide to show how AI uses multiple inputs in real-world applications.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ab9cbb50-bf79-44c2-a6ea-268e5ea35f8d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f2c62f5-2d2c-43f2-a430-fef208bf79e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "44d0d773-274a-4c71-a880-e30205fa6406",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their Problem Solving with AI Unit Guide.****\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Have students list everything they observe in the image found in the \"What's in an image?\" section of Lesson 2 in their Unit Guides. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students are listing observations, listen for students focusing only on objects rather than details like lighting, time of day, or social context. If needed, ask: \"What details beyond objects help describe this image?\"",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Upload Images"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "44d0d773-274a-4c71-a880-e30205fa6406",
        "lesson_activity.key": "745cb615-ab86-444a-8c1c-4f06dcd908a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "808a24be-8606-4d77-b83f-09fa7030c373",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that you have noted what you see in the image, let's see how AI describes it.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "808a24be-8606-4d77-b83f-09fa7030c373",
        "lesson_activity.key": "745cb615-ab86-444a-8c1c-4f06dcd908a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e8fde249-e978-4be0-bbbe-b4a75cb32d27",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 2, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 and 2.\n- **Level #1:** Students review multimodal concepts\n- **Level #2:** Students upload an image and ask AI Chat to describe it. Students should complete the \"What's in an image?\" and \"Privacy and Ethical Concerns\" sections in their Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students noticing unexpected AI-detected details (e.g., time of day, inferred location). If students struggle, ask students, \"Did AI describe something you missed?\" or \"Did AI infer anything beyond what’s in the image?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to compare their observations with AI's response, ask: \"Did AI notice something you didn’t? Why might that be?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e8fde249-e978-4be0-bbbe-b4a75cb32d27",
        "lesson_activity.key": "745cb615-ab86-444a-8c1c-4f06dcd908a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9acdc2c7-e2d9-4742-b808-04deb029c299",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9acdc2c7-e2d9-4742-b808-04deb029c299",
        "lesson_activity.key": "745cb615-ab86-444a-8c1c-4f06dcd908a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1871fd33-a3df-4065-91f4-10048e8fb626",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts:\n- *What should we consider before sharing images online with AI tools?*\n- *What are the benefits and risks of AI interpreting images without human context?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand that AI can infer more than just visible objects in an image, including time, location, and personal details. They should critically evaluate privacy risks and ethical concerns when sharing images with AI.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "For responses related to ethical considerations - If students give general answers, push for specificity by asking: \"What’s one real-world example of when an AI-generated image could cause harm?\"\n\nFor responses related to privacy concerns - If students don’t connect privacy risks to real-world consequences, ask: \"How could an AI misinterpret an image and make incorrect assumptions?\"\n\nIf time allows, prompt the class with: \"Based on what was shared, do you think AI should be allowed to process certain types of images? Why or why not?\" to get students thinking about ethics of AI tool use.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1871fd33-a3df-4065-91f4-10048e8fb626",
        "lesson_activity.key": "745cb615-ab86-444a-8c1c-4f06dcd908a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "caa09099-8ad9-475d-a520-030c2aacab13",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Direct students to Lesson 2, Level 3. Students prompt the chatbot to suggest improvements, first based off of a text-only description and then based on an image.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Scenario-Based Multimodal Prompting"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "caa09099-8ad9-475d-a520-030c2aacab13",
        "lesson_activity.key": "745cb615-ab86-444a-8c1c-4f06dcd908a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b6509910-92ec-4434-961e-72bea07b5782",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Watch for students who struggle to explain why AI's response changed when using text vs. images. If needed, ask: \"What new details did AI include when you used an image? Was the response more specific or more general?\""
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b6509910-92ec-4434-961e-72bea07b5782",
        "lesson_activity.key": "745cb615-ab86-444a-8c1c-4f06dcd908a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1e609ee4-87cf-4f2e-b2fd-b4e60c57afc3",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to Lesson 2, Level 4 to complete the formative assessment.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display students' anonymous responses, and choose one of the three approaches below based on how students did:\n\n- **Option 1: Whole-Class Poll & Debrief (Quick Check-In)**\n\n   - Display the poll results for the multiple choice question.\n\n   - Call on 2-3 students from each answer group (Text Only vs Text +Image) to explain their reasoning\n\n   - Wrap up by asking students: “How does this confirm or challenge what we learned about effective prompting?”\n\n- **Option 2: Small Group Discussion & Class Share-Out (Collaborative)**\n\n   - Assign students to groups of 3-4.\n\n   - Each group discusses: How did AI’s response change when you included an image? and What do you think influenced AI’s different responses?\n\n   - Groups write down 1-2 insights on a shared board (physical or digital).\n\n   - Teacher facilitates a brief whole-class discussion based on key themes.\n\n- **Option 3: Silent Gallery Walk (Reflective)**\n\n   - Post anonymized student responses using the “View Student Responses” Pin Response feature.\n\n   - Students independently respond to pinned responses using:\n\n   - Agree/Disagree: Do they agree with the reasoning? Why?\n\n   - Question: What would they ask this student to clarify?\n\n   - Connection: How does this relate to prior learning?\n\n   - End with whole-class synthesis: What patterns or surprises did students notice?\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This level can be used as a formative assessment to check student understanding of the lesson objectives. Here are things to look for and actions you can take:\n- If most students correctly identified how AI's response changed with an image, reinforce key takeaways with a brief discussion and move forward to the choice-level scenario activity.\n- If responses indicate confusion about why AI responded differently to text vs. image inputs, ask students to revisit AI's descriptions and reflect on what details were added or changed.\n- If students struggle to connect this to effective prompting, review the warm up discussion about media choices and ask: \"How does this activity confirm what we said about text vs. image information?\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1e609ee4-87cf-4f2e-b2fd-b4e60c57afc3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "745cb615-ab86-444a-8c1c-4f06dcd908a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e56352cf-1319-4af5-897e-ac23af992aa5",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e56352cf-1319-4af5-897e-ac23af992aa5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "745cb615-ab86-444a-8c1c-4f06dcd908a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "209ad81f-5295-4c32-8b9e-d8a6ad3cbb34",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we've discussed your findings, let's practice using multimodal AI in a scenario!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "209ad81f-5295-4c32-8b9e-d8a6ad3cbb34",
        "lesson_activity.key": "745cb615-ab86-444a-8c1c-4f06dcd908a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "65b58ef8-3ffe-4d3a-894e-8d5d6cdfe715",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Direct students to Lesson 2, Levels 5 to pick one of the scenarios to practice prompting the AI for suggestions using images and text."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "65b58ef8-3ffe-4d3a-894e-8d5d6cdfe715",
        "lesson_activity.key": "745cb615-ab86-444a-8c1c-4f06dcd908a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b1d63422-2af4-40ab-9447-31921ee8b1ce",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students recognize how AI's response shifts when using text vs. images. If students only describe objects AI listed, ask: \"Did AI provide any deeper insights beyond what you expected?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to experiment with different combinations of text, images, and PDFs to see how AI's responses change. If students finish early or need an extra challenge, suggest trying Option D: Investigative Journalism, where they can analyze how AI generates headlines and summaries from different sources. Have them compare AI-generated headlines with real-world news articles on the same topic. For an added challenge, they can test how changing a single keyword, altering the image, or adding a conflicting source affects AI's response and credibility."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b1d63422-2af4-40ab-9447-31921ee8b1ce",
        "lesson_activity.key": "745cb615-ab86-444a-8c1c-4f06dcd908a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "edf9d5d2-6bc8-4ef5-bdc5-6fb5270967e3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day. Give them 30 seconds to write a response using one of the sentence starters found in the \"Hint' of the Question of the Day for this lesson before having students share with a partner or ask several students to share with the class.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson. If time allows, guide the class discussion toward real-world applications. Use these prompts if needed:\n- Where have you seen multimodal AI used outside of chatbots?\n- How might multimodal AI impact careers in accessibility, medicine, or security?\n- What are examples of AI tools that use images and text together? (e.g., Google Lens, AI-generated captions, AI medical imaging analysis)\n"
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use student responses to gauge understanding. If students struggle to explain how AI's response changed based on input type, revisit earlier examples and prompt students to compare outputs with and without images. If most responses show a strong grasp, move forward."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "edf9d5d2-6bc8-4ef5-bdc5-6fb5270967e3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "45492fd7-beaa-4758-a96d-61a732851d58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "90039bdc-5233-4268-a89f-acc9318f2d86",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "90039bdc-5233-4268-a89f-acc9318f2d86",
        "lesson_activity.key": "45492fd7-beaa-4758-a96d-61a732851d58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "55392f06-5415-457f-a521-bf4a4440b810",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 2, Level 6 to complete the End of Lesson Survey.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "55392f06-5415-457f-a521-bf4a4440b810",
        "lesson_activity.key": "45492fd7-beaa-4758-a96d-61a732851d58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "749c301a-815f-4004-955d-4ce28a8cc9b4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** To help students understand how patterns emerge from large sets of data and how those patterns influence predictions, similar to how neural networks function."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "749c301a-815f-4004-955d-4ce28a8cc9b4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "33ec3f5a-fbfc-48bd-bad3-1efe655aca66"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "93b0bf79-6005-4a98-b30d-b6ec893c7131",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Imagine being in the world’s biggest group chat. If you had access to every message ever sent, what might you notice? What would happen if you read them all?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "93b0bf79-6005-4a98-b30d-b6ec893c7131",
        "lesson_activity.key": "33ec3f5a-fbfc-48bd-bad3-1efe655aca66"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cb6fc2c4-bcaa-4fc9-8387-8b3cd1a1e560",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What would happen if you read every message ever sent in a giant group chat?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students recognize that they would start noticing patterns, commonly used emojis, inside jokes, tone, and conversational flow. This sets up the idea that prediction is based on what comes before—just like how AI models work.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:**  Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What patterns might you pick up over time?*\n- *Could you start predicting what people might say next? How?*\n- *How might your responses be shaped by what you’ve read, rather than your own original thoughts?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize how behavior can become patterned by what they've read—just like AI does. Reinforce that:\n  - AI models also read (or are trained on) millions of examples.\n  - AI doesn't \"think,\" it predicts based on pattern recognition.\n  - The more data it has, the better it becomes at mimicking human-like responses."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cb6fc2c4-bcaa-4fc9-8387-8b3cd1a1e560",
        "lesson_activity.key": "33ec3f5a-fbfc-48bd-bad3-1efe655aca66"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5ed3f073-1275-4dcc-9139-45c247c6ae62",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we've seen how AI can predict responses based on patterns in a group chat, let's take that concept further and explore how AI models, like neural networks, make predictions with limited context and how providing more context can help improve the accuracy of those predictions.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5ed3f073-1275-4dcc-9139-45c247c6ae62",
        "lesson_activity.key": "33ec3f5a-fbfc-48bd-bad3-1efe655aca66"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "42c7b839-62de-47d1-957a-6dd7c4059dc9",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "42c7b839-62de-47d1-957a-6dd7c4059dc9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "33ec3f5a-fbfc-48bd-bad3-1efe655aca66"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b3d927e0-be6e-46f1-9658-d3798f20c747",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** To demonstrate how neural networks predict text based on limited context and show how increasing context improves the accuracy of predictions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in groups of three to five.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each group one copy of the Unplugged Neural Networks activity guide, placed face down. Let students know they'll flip it over when instructed.****\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Introduce the activity. Make sure students understand that the purpose is to simulate how an AI model makes predictions with limited and full context.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Unplugged Neural Network"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b3d927e0-be6e-46f1-9658-d3798f20c747",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4fef1e1b-9b0e-437e-a41b-47114234555b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ef719600-ad08-4334-af6f-bb3ae6febf3d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this activity, your group will simulate how an AI model predicts words. In Round 1, you’ll only get to see the last three words of a sentence before predicting the next word. That's how older models worked—with very limited memory. In Round 2, you'll get to see the entire previous sentence before making your prediction—like modern transformer models, which work with much more context. Let's see how that changes your predictions.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ef719600-ad08-4334-af6f-bb3ae6febf3d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4fef1e1b-9b0e-437e-a41b-47114234555b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "abf08f4e-1187-4d88-84b2-f31e63118071",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to complete Round 1 in their activity guide. Use the steps on the slide to explain the activity procedure and answer any questions. When everyone has added a word, instruct student to unfold the paper and read the full sentence aloud as a group. Have groups to compare their sentences in order to see how similar or different they were. For example, students' sentences could end up like this:\n- Space travel is \n- exciting \n- and \n- dangerous\n- animals \n- live.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Circulate to ensure students aren't peeking back at earlier words or the full sentence.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete Round 2 in their activity guide. Use the steps on the slide to explain the activity procedure and answer any questions. When everyone has contributed, read the full sentence aloud as a group. Direct groups to compare their sentences to Round 1—how did having more context change the predictions? \n\nExample:\n- The exhausted student left school to go home to . . .*rest before starting homework*.\n- The exhausted student left school to go home to . . .*eat dinner with the family*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students read full sentences, listen for students noticing how more words made it easier to choose a logical next word. If students aren’t making the connection, ask: \"What helped you decide which word to add this time?\" and \"Was it easier or harder than the first round?\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *How did having limited context affect predictions?*\n- *What changed when you had access to the entire starting sentence and all words that were added before you?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students recognize that limited context leads to less accurate and more random predictions, while access to more context helps predictions become more logical and connected to previous content. This mirrors how modern AI, like transformers, improves its output by analyzing longer sequences of data.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *In the neural network activity, predictions improved when more context was provided. How do you think this applies to AI prompts?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students recognize that just like their own predictions, AI performs better when it has more context. The more details and structure we give in a prompt, the more accurate, relevant, and helpful the AI's response becomes. Encourage students to connect this back to their experience seeing the full sentence in Round 2.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *neural network*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "abf08f4e-1187-4d88-84b2-f31e63118071",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4fef1e1b-9b0e-437e-a41b-47114234555b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d3959d67-19ad-476a-82ba-25819a1ed9ce",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** To help students understand how large language models (LLMs) like ChatGPT learn from data, recognize patterns, and refine responses through human feedback.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the \"Chatbots and Large Language Models\" video (0:00-1:20).\n\n**Questions to consider with the video:**What is the difference between LLMs and typical neural networks?\n- What is the difference between LLMs and typical neural networks?\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recognize that typical neural networks perform specific tasks, while LLMs process vast text data to generate responses. LLMs predict words using probabilities, making them more flexible and capable of producing human-like text.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *large language model*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the \"Chatbots and Large Language Models\" video (1:20-1:51).\n\n**Questions to consider with the video:**Why is it important for the AI to look at longer sequences such as sentences or paragraphs? How does this relate to the context we provide in our prompts?\n\n- Why is it important for the AI to look at longer sequences such as sentences or paragraphs? How does this relate to the context we provide in our prompts?\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recognize that longer sequences provide more context, leading to more accurate predictions. They connect this to AI prompting, understanding that detailed prompts help AI generate more relevant and coherent responses.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the \"Chatbots and Large Language Models\" video (1:51-2:30).\n\n**Questions to consider with the video:**How does human feedback improve AI responses? Why is it still important to be cautious when using AI, even with fine-tuning?\n\n- How does human feedback improve AI responses? Why is it still important to be cautious when using AI, even with fine-tuning?\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students recognize that human feedback helps AI refine responses by correcting errors and reducing biases. They also understand that, despite fine-tuning, AI can still produce inaccurate or biased outputs, requiring users to think critically about its responses.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *training data*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *training*.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "How LLMs Learn"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d3959d67-19ad-476a-82ba-25819a1ed9ce",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4fef1e1b-9b0e-437e-a41b-47114234555b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d81e8258-9f0d-4f80-8326-2e86a2d73fe5",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** To give students hands-on practice with AI prompting, focusing on how context, examples, and structured inputs improve AI-generated responses. Students will explore real-world career scenarios and experiment with zero-shot, one-shot, and multi-shot prompting to refine AI responses.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Prompting Challenge"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d81e8258-9f0d-4f80-8326-2e86a2d73fe5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4fef1e1b-9b0e-437e-a41b-47114234555b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5fba49f2-e397-4b93-b20d-358a51fb8fe9",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You've seen how AI predictions get better when given more context. Now, you're going to test that idea by giving the AI different types of prompts—starting with no example, then adding one, and finally, adding multiple examples. Try to notice how the responses change at each level.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5fba49f2-e397-4b93-b20d-358a51fb8fe9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4fef1e1b-9b0e-437e-a41b-47114234555b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3a08103b-a0cf-4b22-8f4f-3a34c08ab410",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Level 1 on Code Studio to complete Levels 1 through 3 of the Prompting Challenges activity. For each level, students will choose one of three options based on a real-world career path:\n- **Level 1:** Students provide a basic, unstructured prompt for their chosen career path.\n- **Level 2:** Students add one example to guide the AI's response.\n- **Level 3:** Students refine the prompt with multiple details and structure to improve accuracy."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3a08103b-a0cf-4b22-8f4f-3a34c08ab410",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4fef1e1b-9b0e-437e-a41b-47114234555b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2d56180f-bc0f-4591-9c64-b9f675795a29",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are completing the Prompting Challenges section of their Unit Guide after each level, noting how the AI's responses changed and what role context played in improving them. Listen for how they describe the differences between each AI response as they add more context. Encourage students to be specific in their reflections. If students are unsure what to write, ask:\n- What changed in the AI’s response when you gave an example?\n- Did the response get more accurate, creative, or specific? How do you know?\n- What kind of details made the biggest difference?",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Each level includes multiple career path options. If time allows, encourage students to try more than one scenario to see how prompting techniques apply across different contexts. Ask them whether their observations about AI responses stay consistent across tasks or change depending on the topic."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use student reflections in the Unit Guide to assess how well students understand the role of context and structure in AI responses. Look at their answers to the reflection questions after each level (zero-shot, one-shot, and multi-shot). Based on their responses, determine next steps:\n\n- **If students give vague answers or say AI's response didn't change much across levels:**\n   - Reteach the importance of context by reviewing the neural network activity analogy. Remind students that AI improves with more context and clearer instructions.\n   - Prompt with a discussion question: \"Why would AI struggle to give useful results if your prompt is too short or too open-ended?\"\n   - Small group discussion: Have students compare responses at different levels and identify specific changes in tone, structure, or accuracy.\n- **If students show misunderstanding (e.g., they say multi-shot was worse or don't reference how examples helped):**\n   - Review sample prompt chains together as a class. Ask: \"What kind of details helped this version get better?\"\n   - Have students rewrite one of their weaker prompts from earlier levels using stronger structure or clarity and re-try it with the AI.\n- **If students clearly articulate how adding structure and examples improved the AI's response:**\n   - Move on without reteaching. These students demonstrate understanding of prompt engineering basics.\n   - Optional Challenge: Encourage them to try a second career scenario and see if their insights apply across contexts."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2d56180f-bc0f-4591-9c64-b9f675795a29",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4fef1e1b-9b0e-437e-a41b-47114234555b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0276fc41-120e-4b6e-8237-c62cffc69afa",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day and give students a moment to just think about what they learned today. Let students know that they will be answering the question a little differently today.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to create a short comic strip in their Unit Guide that illustrates something they learned about how AI learns, predicts, or responds to prompts, encouraging humor or creativity. Let students know that this is a creative way to synthesize the lesson. They can be funny, serious, or weird—as long as it's related to how AI works.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students who incorporate ideas like limited context, prediction, pattern recognition, or prompting. If students are stuck, suggest they focus on one concept (e.g., how AI uses training data, how it predicts the next word, or how adding more context makes its output better).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Level 4 to complete the End of Lesson Survey.",
        "name": "Question of the Day Comic Strip"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0276fc41-120e-4b6e-8237-c62cffc69afa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "76c9df59-52e9-4bfc-9c9a-0bd627986299"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "26da31f7-08e8-42ec-ac06-f8558d3a6517",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:**Get students thinking about AI's reliability and how much human involvement they would still want in a task that can now be done by AI.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Say:** AI is being integrated into many real-world tasks. Some people are excited about this, while others have concerns.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Inform students that they will be presented with different scenarios on the next few slides. They should think critically about the level of AI involvement they would prefer or be comfortable with for each scenario, then vote with their fingers.\n",
        "name": "AI Reliability Voting",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time allows, you can instead have students line up in your classroom from \"Just Human\" on one end and \"Just AI\" on the other and give them a minute to discuss their reasons for where they lined up along the spectrum with those around them."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "26da31f7-08e8-42ec-ac06-f8558d3a6517",
        "lesson_activity.key": "647987e3-6be9-4ed5-a17d-6967680451a9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e6dfd877-e325-4319-8a93-241acc96b0c3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e6dfd877-e325-4319-8a93-241acc96b0c3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "647987e3-6be9-4ed5-a17d-6967680451a9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e6ecbfb3-1808-4604-b386-02956b70cc34",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Present the first real-world AI use case: diagnosing medical issues. Ask students to vote on the level of AI involvement they would prefer for this use case. After students vote, ask a couple students from each option (0-1 finger, 2-3 fingers, 4-5 fingers) to explain their reasoning. Students should recognize that AI has strengths but also clear limitations that require human oversight. The goal is to try to get students to begin considering what makes AI reliable vs. risky in different applications.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to think critically about the risks vs. benefits, prompt them with follow-up questions, such as \"What’s the worst-case scenario if AI makes a mistake in this task?\" or \"How could AI and humans work together in this situation?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e6ecbfb3-1808-4604-b386-02956b70cc34",
        "lesson_activity.key": "647987e3-6be9-4ed5-a17d-6967680451a9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d0c0cea-00ba-4711-a34d-3b9b53d5f26f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d0c0cea-00ba-4711-a34d-3b9b53d5f26f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "647987e3-6be9-4ed5-a17d-6967680451a9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8c72db08-ea4e-460c-9ab3-5e8b23f3011a",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Present the second real-world AI use case: grading essays. Ask students to vote on the level of AI involvement they would prefer for this use case. After students vote, ask a couple students from each option to explain their reasoning.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students say AI isn't useful for grading, ask: \"Could AI help teachers save time?\" or \"If AI misses deeper meaning in writing, how could we still use it effectively?\" Bring up tools like Grammarly—AI helps with mechanics, but teachers provide feedback on ideas."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8c72db08-ea4e-460c-9ab3-5e8b23f3011a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "647987e3-6be9-4ed5-a17d-6967680451a9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7cd65f16-4ec2-485a-865a-236e4965b61d",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7cd65f16-4ec2-485a-865a-236e4965b61d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "647987e3-6be9-4ed5-a17d-6967680451a9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fdcefb2b-ea65-40fa-ba8b-74f34688a261",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Present the third real-world AI use case: driving a school bus. Ask students to vote on the level of AI involvement they would prefer for this use case. After students vote, ask a couple students from each option to explain their reasoning.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students say AI should fully replace bus drivers, ask: \"What happens if a child runs into the street unexpectedly?\" or \"Can AI handle a traffic situation as well as a human driver?\" Connect this to real-world examples like Tesla's autopilot mode—it assists but doesn't replace drivers."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fdcefb2b-ea65-40fa-ba8b-74f34688a261",
        "lesson_activity.key": "647987e3-6be9-4ed5-a17d-6967680451a9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "697da911-4088-408b-aeb8-83ba9bd59179",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "697da911-4088-408b-aeb8-83ba9bd59179",
        "lesson_activity.key": "647987e3-6be9-4ed5-a17d-6967680451a9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "575222ca-28a7-48a1-ac22-0059d4975160",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "575222ca-28a7-48a1-ac22-0059d4975160",
        "lesson_activity.key": "647987e3-6be9-4ed5-a17d-6967680451a9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "23fe5f0e-3a01-4ea2-8afd-a6a896c6355b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:**Introduce students to AI-generated hallucinations and why AI gets things wrong.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Ask students to analyze where AI went wrong. Prompt them to identify errors in AI's response and discuss why they happened. Encourage students to look for patterns in the errors. Give students a minute to share with a partner before sharing as a class. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen for students pointing out how AI generates words based on patterns rather than understanding. If students struggle to identify why \"Micken\" or \"Beta\" is incorrect, ask: \"What pattern do you see in AI's mistakes? How does AI choose words?\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *How do you know AI's response is incorrect?*\n- *What does this tell us about how AI generates responses?*\n- *How does this show the importance of fact-checking AI outputs?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand that AI predicts based on probability, not actual knowledge. The goal is to get students to begin considering why AI makes errors and when it should be fact-checked. Example student responses may include: \n- \"AI doesn't actually know meanings; it just predicts words that commonly follow each other\"\n- \"It made up words because it’s trying to complete a pattern rather than understanding the meaning\"\n- \"That means AI can make errors in more serious situations too, like if it made up medical information.\"\n",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "AI Hallucination Example and Discussion",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are struggling to articulate why AI makes mistakes, prompt them with: \"Does AI understand language like a human, or is it just following patterns?\" or \"What would happen if we trusted AI without checking its facts?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "23fe5f0e-3a01-4ea2-8afd-a6a896c6355b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9e2d8841-e2b5-44af-a709-3dd06c595410",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9e2d8841-e2b5-44af-a709-3dd06c595410",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c36975b5-83e8-4b06-b2fe-698eb2042906",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their Problem Solving with AI Unit Guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c36975b5-83e8-4b06-b2fe-698eb2042906",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ea8bd4b8-7c1e-4cbf-a966-608994e87e22",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "AI doesn't \"think\" like a human – it predicts based on probability and past data. AI can make up words, facts, or quotes because it's trying to complete a pattern, not verify truth. This occurs when the most probable response isn't accurate or factual.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ea8bd4b8-7c1e-4cbf-a966-608994e87e22",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b16d27cf-10c4-4ea7-be0d-b238fabb3e11",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *hallucination*.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Help students connect this definition to real-world AI failures. Explain that AI doesn’t know \"Micken\" isn't a real word—it just predicts what's most likely to come next based on training data. This is why AI sometimes generates confident but completely false responses."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b16d27cf-10c4-4ea7-be0d-b238fabb3e11",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f68708da-dc85-4b00-830f-f8e27eb380b5",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f68708da-dc85-4b00-830f-f8e27eb380b5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5250b0cb-10ac-44f9-a5dc-358a321321b6",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain that AI doesn't verify information before providing a response - it just outputs what it predicts is most likely to sound correct. This is why humans should fact-check any AI-generated responses before trusting them, even when the hallucination seems plausible. Not fact-checking can lead to misinformation.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You do not need to go in-depth into misinformation and fact-checking as this will be covered in an upcoming lesson. Use this as an opportunity to get students to start thinking about the importance of fact-checking."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5250b0cb-10ac-44f9-a5dc-358a321321b6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fef12bdd-6fc6-435f-8324-3a3e5f1e0764",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:**Allow students to experiment with AI capabilities and determine where AI performs well vs. where it struggles. Encourage students to compare AI-generated vs. human-generated responses to develop the Critical Consumer mindset.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "AI vs Human Tasks"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fef12bdd-6fc6-435f-8324-3a3e5f1e0764",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "28af6a8b-bbcd-409a-8cca-37c960122d22",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We just saw an example of AI making up words. Now, we're going to test AI with different types of tasks to see what it does well and where it struggles.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "28af6a8b-bbcd-409a-8cca-37c960122d22",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f22be262-af56-494e-9f98-576f83cff9a1",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students into pairs for the purpose of having a thought partner to share experiences and ranking with for the next activity.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 3 to test AI's performance on different tasks. Students should complete the \"Human vs AI Response Comparison\" section of their Unit Guide as they interact with each task.\n- **Level #1:** Students test AI's ability to solve a math problem. They rate how well a human would do and how the AI did.\n- **Level #2:** Students test AI's ability to answer a creative or tricky question. They rate how well a human would do and how the AI did.\n- **Level #3:** Students test AI's ability to provide historical or technical information. They rate how well a human would do and how the AI did.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f22be262-af56-494e-9f98-576f83cff9a1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ca48ef82-9e98-4564-bb2d-a5ec8119d30a",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are sharing and comparing results and rankings for each task with their thought partner. Observe how students are ranking AI vs human performance in the AI vs Human Response Comparison. If students are unsure, ask: \"What criteria are you using to decide whether AI or a human is better at this task?\"",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Each level has multiple options for students to choose from as tasks to provide to the AI. If time allows, encourage students to test multiple types of tasks to see if their rankings remain consistent."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ca48ef82-9e98-4564-bb2d-a5ec8119d30a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f9e48f49-d658-464b-af9a-9ce98d817e44",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f9e48f49-d658-464b-af9a-9ce98d817e44",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1035a1bd-23d9-43d1-8e08-f482e60b7213",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What tasks was AI best at? Why?*\n- *Where did it struggle? Why?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that AI excels at structured, data-driven tasks but struggles with creativity and reasoning. Aim to get students to connect AI's limitations to its training data and probability-based responses.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to identify patterns in AI's performance, ask: \"What did AI do well across multiple tasks?\" or \"Did AI struggle with logic-based tasks or tasks that required creativity?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1035a1bd-23d9-43d1-8e08-f482e60b7213",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6922fc06-12ba-4499-92c1-89e1d663e485",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6922fc06-12ba-4499-92c1-89e1d663e485",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8604fcc9-c254-46e5-ab9c-cc8447a7f458",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that AI is really good at things like math, but it doesn't have human intuition or logic. Due to hallucinations, it needs to be fact-checked.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students assume AI is better just because it's faster, ask: \"When does accuracy matter more than speed? Can AI make fast but incorrect decisions?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8604fcc9-c254-46e5-ab9c-cc8447a7f458",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "054451f7-01ba-4e25-9c07-1f4d39aaa1cf",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "054451f7-01ba-4e25-9c07-1f4d39aaa1cf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6e74edfc-0c30-4c30-8a8e-b1649223546c",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *How did AI's responses compare to human-generated responses?*\n- *Would you trust AI's responses without fact-checking?*\n- *Why or why not?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students develop the Critical Consumer mindset by questioning where AI-generated content needs human oversight.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students appear to struggle to make the connection between hallucinations and the tasks they tested, ask the follow up questions: \"How does what we just tested compare to the hallucination example? Did AI make similar mistakes?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6e74edfc-0c30-4c30-8a8e-b1649223546c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d3665066-60bc-4033-881e-8b3adfb5e562",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d3665066-60bc-4033-881e-8b3adfb5e562",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "71ceb1f6-8410-4f4b-a0f2-891eba3e4a13",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we've ranked AI's performance, let's think about how this applies to real-world careers. Do we trust AI to handle critical tasks in medicine, law, travel, or writing?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "71ceb1f6-8410-4f4b-a0f2-891eba3e4a13",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ce12e241-ac6a-40bc-b7d8-32903c57be68",
      "position": 20,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 4 to complete the formative assessment."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ce12e241-ac6a-40bc-b7d8-32903c57be68",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dd7cf5ff-2cd8-40e6-8aa1-b41cdd3925e6",
      "position": 21,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display students' anonymous responses and ask students \"What do you notice?\" and \"What do you wonder?\" Have students discuss with a partner before asking for a couple volunteers to share.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students only focus on AI's benefits, ask: \"What are the risks if AI makes a mistake in this career?\" or \"Would an AI error have minor or serious consequences in this field? Why?\""
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This level can be used as a formative assessment to check student understanding of the lesson objectives. Here are things to look for and actions you can take:\n- If students assume AI can fully replace humans, revisit the AI vs. Humans – Strengths and Weaknesses slide to reinforce AI's limitations.\n- If students struggle to justify their reasoning, prompt them to connect their responses back to their AI vs. Human Response Comparison rankings.\n- If students demonstrate strong understanding, move on to the wrap-up discussion.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dd7cf5ff-2cd8-40e6-8aa1-b41cdd3925e6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3fd1c824-c2e7-441f-9824-9e4771bb87cf"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4dfebd59-348e-4688-bfbb-a88b3959adda",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:**Ensure all students reflect on AI's strengths and weaknesses as a collaborator by sharing their insights in small groups. Reinforce the Critical Consumer mindset by encouraging students to verbalize when AI is useful vs. when human reasoning is needed.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to answer the Question of the Day in their Unit Guide.\n",
        "name": "Question of the Day Reflection",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to differentiate AI's strengths from its weaknesses, revisit the AI vs. Humans – Strengths & Weaknesses slide and discuss specific examples. If students make strong, specific comparisons, move on to the Pass the Mic activity."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4dfebd59-348e-4688-bfbb-a88b3959adda",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7a8bf135-d4c2-4f99-82da-9bd77d2ce84c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6db652c0-b6ce-4740-b8b0-6c9cc1f357ca",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6db652c0-b6ce-4740-b8b0-6c9cc1f357ca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7a8bf135-d4c2-4f99-82da-9bd77d2ce84c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "306b90cd-aa0a-438d-8a65-a1253a6c9af5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Have students form small groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Explain that now that they have reflected in their Unit Guide, they will share key takeaways with their group. Explain that the \"Pass the Mic\" discussion is designed so that everyone gets a chance to share. Each person will share their answer to the Question of the Day in one or two sentences and then \"pass the mic\" so that everyone has a turn.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students share in their groups:\n- Listen for common themes and misconceptions such as:\n   - Are students clearly identifying AI's strengths and weaknesses?\n   - Are students misunderstanding AI's capabilities (e.g., assuming AI \"thinks\" like a human)?\n- Prompt deeper thinking with guiding questions such as:\n   - Did AI ever surprise you with what it could or couldn't do?\n   - Would you trust AI more or less after today's lesson?\n   - Did anyone in your group have a different perspective that made you think differently?\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time allows, facilitate a full-class discussion of the QotD. Consider asking students to raise their hands if they heard a new perspective in their group that made them think differently.\n- If students only state a general opinion (e.g., \"AI is good at math\"), follow up with: \"What makes AI good at that task? Is it better than a human?\" or \"Can you give an example of when AI would fail at that same task?\"\n- If some students are not engaging in discussion, ask them directly: \"What did you write down in your Unit Guide? Can you share one thing that stood out to you?\" or \"Did you hear something from your group that you agree or disagree with?\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "306b90cd-aa0a-438d-8a65-a1253a6c9af5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7a8bf135-d4c2-4f99-82da-9bd77d2ce84c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7fe1e2b7-7186-45d5-a385-1249c687e531",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7fe1e2b7-7186-45d5-a385-1249c687e531",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7a8bf135-d4c2-4f99-82da-9bd77d2ce84c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c5b13414-c0d3-4b33-acb8-9f65a786add8",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 5 to complete the End of Lesson Survey.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c5b13414-c0d3-4b33-acb8-9f65a786add8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7a8bf135-d4c2-4f99-82da-9bd77d2ce84c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b0b8ef13-9b12-4af8-8522-6c68009247eb",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Ask the class for a topic (e.g., space, animals, history, music, etc.).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use Lesson 5, Level 1 to demo entering the following prompt: \"Tell me 2 truths and a lie about [insert topic]. Don't tell me which ones are truths or lies.\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students partner up and try to guess which AI-generated statements are true and which is the lie.\n",
        "name": "Two Truths and a Lie"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b0b8ef13-9b12-4af8-8522-6c68009247eb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d0142471-9b3e-4d4c-a652-079bac60bb62"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "330f3a5a-1a4a-478c-b285-d5051a3c7e06",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "AI might not always produce the results that is expected. The result might even be contradictory. Therefore, fact-checking AI's results is an important step of the process.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "330f3a5a-1a4a-478c-b285-d5051a3c7e06",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d0142471-9b3e-4d4c-a652-079bac60bb62"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "516a79d4-eca9-4bcb-aed7-0ef73134038b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Demonstrate fact-checking by researching online using Google and/or credible websites to verify which statements are true and which is a lie.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *Why might AI generate a lie or inaccurate information?*\n- *How do we ensure accuracy when using AI?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand that AI generates responses based on patterns in data rather than verified facts. They should discuss how AI lacks direct knowledge, can misinterpret ambiguous prompts, and sometimes \"hallucinates\" information because it is designed to predict plausible-sounding text rather than confirm truth. Students highlight the importance of human judgement in verifying AI-generated content. Students should identify fact-checking strategies, such as cross-referencing multiple reliable sources (using official or expert-verified information) and critically analyze responses for logical consistency.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "516a79d4-eca9-4bcb-aed7-0ef73134038b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d0142471-9b3e-4d4c-a652-079bac60bb62"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c86228d5-30ff-4ec0-998a-66e2fbdafc7f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *contradiction*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the*Contradictions in Real World Contexts*activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Using their activity guide, students will review two contradictory AI responses from a telehealth chatbot.\n- **Step 1:** Students review both AI-generated responses.\n- **Step 2:** Students highlight contradictions, vague statements, or misleading claims, such as the conflicting advice on whether or not immediate medical attention is necessary.\n- **Step 3:** Students fact-check the AI's claims using reliable sources (e.g., trusted medical websites or professional guidelines).\n- **Step 4:** Students refine the provided prompt to get a more consistent and clearer response from the AI.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *How does the AI's lack of specialization in the medical field contribute to contradictions?*\n- *How can fact-checking and prompt refinement help improve AI-generated responses in real-world contexts?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognized that AI models do not have deep expertise like medical professionals. They should discuss how AI relies on broad datasets that may contain conflicting or outdated information, which leads to contradictions. Students should understand that fact-checking ensures accuracy by verifying AI-generated information against trusted sources. They should also recognize that refining prompts (e.g. specifying a reliable source, adding context, etc.) helps AI produce clearer and more relevant responses.\n",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Contradictions in Real-World Contexts"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c86228d5-30ff-4ec0-998a-66e2fbdafc7f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "009fc6b4-9387-40c9-be4f-d5cbf3219fdd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9f1da3e0-f0b4-4342-aa8c-62930b494a5c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "AI models do not have deep expertise like medical professionals. AI relies on broad datasets that may contain conflicting or outdated information, which leads to contradictions. Fact-checking ensures accuracy by verifying AI-generated information against trusted sources. Refining prompts by doing things like specifying a reliable source or adding context helps AI produce clearer and more relevant responses.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9f1da3e0-f0b4-4342-aa8c-62930b494a5c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "009fc6b4-9387-40c9-be4f-d5cbf3219fdd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7bec07c4-bdc4-46e4-a3f1-7c240fa46d20",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the differences between where an AI and a medical professional acquire information."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7bec07c4-bdc4-46e4-a3f1-7c240fa46d20",
        "lesson_activity.key": "009fc6b4-9387-40c9-be4f-d5cbf3219fdd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f858a9fa-c7cf-437b-bb5f-7cd3bf16355d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 3 to complete Levels 3 through 6. Students choose a different topic in this choice level (e.g., government, nutrition, science, law, social media). In pairs, students practice with the various forms of questioning provided and discuss the results.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "AI Contradictions in Practice"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f858a9fa-c7cf-437b-bb5f-7cd3bf16355d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "009fc6b4-9387-40c9-be4f-d5cbf3219fdd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7b9a6d70-a33f-4442-bc55-4c4b1db1e401",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to review the three different ways in which students were asked to refine the prompt in the previous activity.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *context*.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7b9a6d70-a33f-4442-bc55-4c4b1db1e401",
        "lesson_activity.key": "009fc6b4-9387-40c9-be4f-d5cbf3219fdd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "398d1d06-9b00-4726-9f0a-c14752d7ad65",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 7. In pairs, students practice prompting the AI Chat with different framings of their own questions to see if they can produce AI contradictions and can experience themselves how their framing can alter the response an AI outputs."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "398d1d06-9b00-4726-9f0a-c14752d7ad65",
        "lesson_activity.key": "009fc6b4-9387-40c9-be4f-d5cbf3219fdd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8a52ef56-3107-46fb-a91e-8718f59a9259",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 8 to complete the formative assessment on Levels 8 and 9.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This level can be used as a formative assessment to check student understanding of the lesson objectives. Here are things to look for and actions you can take:\n- Review responses to see whether students can explain why AI might contradict itself and how that differs from human contradictions. If students struggle to articulate these differences, have them revisit the telehealth example (or another real-world scenario) and prompt them to highlight exactly where the AI's contradiction arose—and contrast it with how a human might revise a diagnosis after new data.\n- See whether students can identify specific potential harms, and if not, direct them back to the telehealth chatbot examples provided in the lesson. You could also show short clips or articles about AI's role in other high-stakes fields (finance, insurance) to further underscore the importance of verifying AI outputs.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8a52ef56-3107-46fb-a91e-8718f59a9259",
        "lesson_activity.key": "009fc6b4-9387-40c9-be4f-d5cbf3219fdd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "36af8790-72ac-42de-93a6-e95c376c282d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their Problem Solving with AI Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  In their Unit Guide, students answer the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students make a prediction about how the ability of AI to contradict itself might evolve over the next 10 years.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 6 to complete the End of Lesson Survey.\n",
        "name": "Future Predictions"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "36af8790-72ac-42de-93a6-e95c376c282d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "715f9050-e439-46a3-b26f-3a7727d74ef6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cd700bc7-01b5-4ab0-940f-9837a5f8ccf8",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "AI models learn by analyzing vast amounts of online data. They recognize patterns and use them to make predictions. Let's explore how this works by seeing what AI might assume about a nurse.",
        "name": "AI Assumptions",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cd700bc7-01b5-4ab0-940f-9837a5f8ccf8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fd567135-5dda-4251-a61a-24ed3ac771f0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6805b743-9718-4d8f-b031-08f8f13ba220",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to a web browser. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Students go to images.google.com and search for \"nurse\" and analyze the results.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:**  Encourage them to look beyond the first row of images.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *If an AI model were trained on this dataset, how might this pattern of bias in search results influence AI-generated text responses?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should connect bias in search results to how AI models learn patterns and replicate biases. For example, if the AI model were to train on the results of the Google Image search it might start associating \"nurse\" with \"woman\".\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you want to take this discussion one level deeper, you may choose to ask: \"How do these biases get reinforced when AI is asked similar questions?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6805b743-9718-4d8f-b031-08f8f13ba220",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fd567135-5dda-4251-a61a-24ed3ac771f0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "48702cac-c4eb-4a8b-ba15-ff2a8d8ea880",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "48702cac-c4eb-4a8b-ba15-ff2a8d8ea880",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fd567135-5dda-4251-a61a-24ed3ac771f0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a1743373-db1f-4e3a-b7f7-85795225a4cf",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a1743373-db1f-4e3a-b7f7-85795225a4cf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fd567135-5dda-4251-a61a-24ed3ac771f0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e71d7ebc-c151-49d4-af63-aa3959cfd475",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:**Students explore AI's assumptions and analyze how training data influences AI-generated responses. Students analyze AI's initial responses, identify potential biases, and refine their prompts to create more neutral and inclusive descriptions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their Problem Solving with AI Unit Guide.\n",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Bias Intro: Describe a ____"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e71d7ebc-c151-49d4-af63-aa3959cfd475",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "363ddc4b-853a-43fd-8ca7-4608e6bfb666",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "AI learns from patterns in data, but that data isn't always balanced or fair. If certain perspectives or groups are overrepresented, AI will reflect those patterns in its responses. This can lead to AI making assumptions that don’t accurately represent the full picture.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "363ddc4b-853a-43fd-8ca7-4608e6bfb666",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1247f6ca-1245-4d58-99ae-4eb611cdc44e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *AI bias*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Understanding Bias activity guide.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1247f6ca-1245-4d58-99ae-4eb611cdc44e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "74cca4ff-6b58-4923-8a6a-9ac65b6068c1",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "AI generates responses based on patterns in its training data. But what happens when those patterns reflect assumptions about people and professions? Let's investigate by asking AI to describe two different jobs and analyzing its responses.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "74cca4ff-6b58-4923-8a6a-9ac65b6068c1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "17c65615-318a-4287-9113-18fe72e83aab",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 1 to explore AI-generated descriptions of different professions – a nurse and doctor. Students should complete the AI Bias Analysis section of their activity guide as they interact with each task."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "17c65615-318a-4287-9113-18fe72e83aab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bab10394-ae83-406d-9dfe-2edecc639312",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *Did AI assume a default identity in either of the prompts?*\n- *Did the responses differ in the tone, assumptions, or characteristics included?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that AI descriptions reflect patterns in training data, which may reinforce stereotypes or assumptions. They should identify differences in language, gender associations, or implied expertise in AI-generated responses.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to articulate differences, prompt them with:\n- \"What words or phrases stand out in each description?\"\n- \"Does AI use the same level of professionalism, detail, or authority in both responses?\"\n- \"Would changing the wording of the prompt lead to a different response?\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bab10394-ae83-406d-9dfe-2edecc639312",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24869a17-daaf-4ec3-8ebe-45e0a2b2d1dc",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24869a17-daaf-4ec3-8ebe-45e0a2b2d1dc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3dcb1663-2ffe-44b1-9241-66ac7e1c42a9",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we've seen how AI describes different professions, let's take it a step further. AI doesn't generate biased responses on purpose—it reflects patterns in the data it has learned from. But we can adjust our inputs to get better, more neutral results. Let's try to refine our prompts and see how AI responds.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3dcb1663-2ffe-44b1-9241-66ac7e1c42a9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3168e3fc-021c-4b8d-bbc1-b7cc7e74b0e8",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 1. Refine the original prompts to improve neutrality. Students document their refined prompts and compare AI's new responses in the AI Bias Analysis Chart section of their activity guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3168e3fc-021c-4b8d-bbc1-b7cc7e74b0e8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3339a2c7-d967-4aed-b6d4-f664f7cd0f2c",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What factors in AI's training data may have led to this bias we uncovered?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for students to bring up bias in the datasets, connecting back to the warm up activity, other examples they may be familiar with, or their own lived experiences.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3339a2c7-d967-4aed-b6d4-f664f7cd0f2c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1a4602fc-97e1-44dd-85f6-329ad4cd4d0f",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We've explored how AI bias emerges and how we can adjust prompts to reduce it. Now, let's think about what AI developers can do to make AI systems more fair and representative.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1a4602fc-97e1-44dd-85f6-329ad4cd4d0f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6afeacba-2aca-433f-89de-aa7884ab28f9",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 2 to complete the formative assessment.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** \n- Students answer the multiple-select question: \"How could AI developers make adjustments to reduce bias?\"\n- Use the \"View Student Responses\" feature to analyze the class results.\n- Ask students: \"What do you notice?\" and \"What do you wonder?\" Have them discuss with a partner before selecting a few volunteers to share.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Emphasize that AI bias is not just a coding issue—it's a data issue. Many students assume developers can \"fix\" bias with a simple programming change, but bias originates from the datasets AI is trained on."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This activity helps assess student understanding of AI bias mitigation strategies. Based on student responses, take the following actions:\n- If most students select the correct answer (B), proceed to the next activity (AI Audit).\n- If some students are confused, have them pair up and explain their reasoning to each other. Then, re-pose the question and have students show their answers using their fingers (1-4) before moving on.\n- If many students select incorrect answers (A, C, or D),\n- Revisit key slides that explain how bias comes from data, not just code.\n- Clarify that more data isn't always better—biased data will still lead to biased AI.\n- Have students answer the question again using a show of fingers before transitioning.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6afeacba-2aca-433f-89de-aa7884ab28f9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bb44f824-0a3e-4409-9307-8deb79feff2f",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:**Students analyze bias in decision-making by comparing their own candidate selection process with AI’s and exploring how training data influences AI’s choices.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "AI Audit Challenges"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bb44f824-0a3e-4409-9307-8deb79feff2f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c18a462c-db3e-46d4-afbb-5c688d23300c",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "AI is increasingly being used to make important decisions—hiring employees, admitting students, and even determining which patients receive medical care first. But how do we know if AI is making fair and unbiased choices? Today, you'll take on a decision-making role and compare your choices to AI's.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c18a462c-db3e-46d4-afbb-5c688d23300c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d7255ef4-c82e-4d0c-8a8d-e5508b961c13",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 3. Students choose one decision-making role:\n- **Hiring Manager:** Selects top candidates for job interviews.\n- **College Admissions Officer:** Picks students for acceptance.\n- **Hospital Triage Nurse:** Prioritizes patients for urgent care.\n\nThen students review the candidate pool and select two candidates based on their qualifications. They record and justify selections in the activity guide.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d7255ef4-c82e-4d0c-8a8d-e5508b961c13",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4532c468-40b1-4574-aed5-c5b011f98c47",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:**  Listen for students discussing why certain candidates stood out over others. If students struggle, ask:\n- *\"What specific qualifications made you choose these candidates?\"*\n- *\"Did you consider factors beyond qualifications, like personal background?\"*\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4532c468-40b1-4574-aed5-c5b011f98c47",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "df257efa-9ae4-4d2f-b6b0-42259943910c",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now, let's see how AI makes the same decision. AI doesn't have opinions or instincts—it relies on patterns in data. You'll ask AI to select candidates for your decision-making role, analyze its reasoning, and compare it to your own. Finally, you'll refine your prompt to see if AI's choices can better match your priorities.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "df257efa-9ae4-4d2f-b6b0-42259943910c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ff9095e1-3065-451e-a087-a9f150839c7b",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 4, where they will ask AI Chat to select candidates for the same decision-making role they previously chose. Students will then compare AI's selections to their own. After reviewing AI's choices, students will refine their prompt to better align with their group's priorities, specifying which qualities AI should prioritize while abstracting away irrelevant details.\n\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ff9095e1-3065-451e-a087-a9f150839c7b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "54f788a7-6ba7-4518-a058-938dc59eebbd",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Form student groups of three, ensuring each student has a different role, to share their findings.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *alignment* and share two mitigation strategies for reducing AI bias.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "54f788a7-6ba7-4518-a058-938dc59eebbd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e3bb530f-cc33-48de-8e93-9c2cc528a69f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b5371885-7306-444b-bc02-c87b4737aee0",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** In the Unit Guide, students reflect on 3 examples of AI bias from this lesson, 2 things to help reduce AI bias, and 1 cause of AI bias. After, they discuss their responses with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Assign students numbers in small groups and give them a discussion prompt. After a short discussion, randomly call out a number—students with that number share their group's response.\n",
        "name": "3-2-1 Reflection and Discussion",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Rotate which number is called in future discussions to ensure all students participate over time."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b5371885-7306-444b-bc02-c87b4737aee0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "07889db2-63fa-4b7e-8aac-9a985a7b16eb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c6feed9d-56d8-4358-adc3-e87f6becba01",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c6feed9d-56d8-4358-adc3-e87f6becba01",
        "lesson_activity.key": "07889db2-63fa-4b7e-8aac-9a985a7b16eb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ed51cc18-6caf-4e06-b4e1-d36d097e5073",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Key Vocabulary.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 5 to complete the End of Lesson Survey.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ed51cc18-6caf-4e06-b4e1-d36d097e5073",
        "lesson_activity.key": "07889db2-63fa-4b7e-8aac-9a985a7b16eb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ba3d89ce-d681-4736-ac0a-5d679ab9d0f5",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:**Reveal how AI can generate misinformation by mimicking human knowledge gaps.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in groups of four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each group 12-15 sticky notes. Each students needs at least three.\n",
        "name": "Hallucination Chain",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If needed, adjust the number of sticky notes based on group size so each student has three.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ba3d89ce-d681-4736-ac0a-5d679ab9d0f5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32017c6a-f659-45f9-a08f-90abf2fe94ca"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5d7a149d-2127-4c69-834a-8abc4b8bd3eb",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5d7a149d-2127-4c69-834a-8abc4b8bd3eb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32017c6a-f659-45f9-a08f-90abf2fe94ca"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9f7955b9-5a69-4b77-a003-50512ea98af5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Have students each write three facts about the Great Wall of China on sticky notes - one fact per sticky note. Tell students that if they are unsure, they can make up something that sounds believable.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check that students are writing individual facts and not collaborating at this stage. If students hesitate, remind them that they can create facts if they’re unsure.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Have groups examine their sticky notes and categorize them into similarities, differences, contradictions, and inaccuracies.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Watch for students who categorize everything as similar or accurate—prompt them to look for contradictions.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle, prompt them with: \"How do we know if something is inaccurate?\" or \"What makes two facts similar?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9f7955b9-5a69-4b77-a003-50512ea98af5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32017c6a-f659-45f9-a08f-90abf2fe94ca"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dcba93cb-41df-4a03-846d-710f8918ce5f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dcba93cb-41df-4a03-846d-710f8918ce5f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32017c6a-f659-45f9-a08f-90abf2fe94ca"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "55675414-12a5-4e79-9910-50710cc44c48",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What might happen if we published these \"facts\" on a public website?*\n- *How does this activity mimic the way that AI generates responses?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Guide students to recognize just like we created statements that sounded true but weren't, AI can hallucinate and generate misinformation that seems convincing. AI models learn from human input—if that input contains misinformation, AI can amplify and spread it.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "55675414-12a5-4e79-9910-50710cc44c48",
        "lesson_activity.key": "32017c6a-f659-45f9-a08f-90abf2fe94ca"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d00307f2-7dd1-460c-aad2-1785b69cb21b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:**Show how AI hallucinations cause harm in real-world applications.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:**  Give each student a copy of the Hallucination Case Studies Activity Guide and a Jigsaw Article.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that students will read about real-world AI hallucinations in industries like law, travel, healthcare, and transportation. They will read independently first, then discuss their findings with their group.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Instruct students to read their assigned Jigsaw Article individually. Each student should annotate their article by highlighting key terms (e.g., AI Hallucination, accuracy, fairness, impact) and writing notes or questions in the margins. Students should also answer the reflection questions in their Hallucination Case Studies Activity Guide​ as they read their article.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Walk around and check that students are actively annotating and engaging with the text, jotting down notes in their activity guides. If students struggle, ask: \n- \"What was the AI hallucination in your article?\" \n- \"What was the real-world impact?\" \n- \"Would a human have made the same mistake?\"\n\nIf students are only highlighting without writing notes, encourage them to add margin notes or questions to deepen their analysis.\n",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Hallucination Case Studies",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students finish early, have them jot down a real-world example where they've seen AI generate incorrect or misleading information (e.g., a chatbot making up a statistic, an AI-generated image mislabeling an object). This helps students connect their reading to prior knowledge and real-world experiences."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d00307f2-7dd1-460c-aad2-1785b69cb21b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5e40a8f5-29bf-4a8d-bb12-2f541ab8a364"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "243b0c00-6d5b-475a-a78d-2ca42a658e19",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "243b0c00-6d5b-475a-a78d-2ca42a658e19",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5e40a8f5-29bf-4a8d-bb12-2f541ab8a364"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "311e9505-2ea3-44da-84f7-a06a5262d19f",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Have students share their article summaries with their group members. Each student should briefly explain what their article was about, what the AI hallucination was, and its consequences. After each student shares, the group discusses the real-world impact of AI hallucinations and what could have been done differently.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen for common themes in student discussions. If students struggle to identify AI's impact, ask: \n- \"Who was affected by this AI mistake?\"\n- \"What industries could be impacted by similar hallucinations?\"\n- \"What steps could have been taken to avoid this hallucination?\"\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If groups struggle to connect their article’s AI hallucination to broader issues, encourage them to think about similar situations in other fields (e.g., misinformation in journalism, AI-generated legal errors, biased hiring algorithms)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "311e9505-2ea3-44da-84f7-a06a5262d19f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5e40a8f5-29bf-4a8d-bb12-2f541ab8a364"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9cf531a6-6e98-4d08-bd8b-cd7b42aaa576",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:**Students get practice with evaluating AI responses that contain hallucinations.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Reduce Hallucinations and Assessment"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9cf531a6-6e98-4d08-bd8b-cd7b42aaa576",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5e40a8f5-29bf-4a8d-bb12-2f541ab8a364"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5683a59a-ab71-44e6-b12f-082a9f66a108",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we've seen the real-world impact of AI hallucinations, let's look at three strategies we can use to minimize misinformation when working with AI.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5683a59a-ab71-44e6-b12f-082a9f66a108",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5e40a8f5-29bf-4a8d-bb12-2f541ab8a364"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a1d64ebc-6095-4ca9-ad9f-e384590e6d27",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain how it helps prevent AI misinformation. Use real-world examples where possible, such as AI misquoting sources or giving outdated information. Remind students that AI doesn't fact-check—it predicts likely responses based on past data.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to connect these strategies to their own experiences using AI tools or searching for information online. If students struggle to see the relevance, ask: \"What happens if you search for a fact and only look at the first result without verifying it?\""
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a1d64ebc-6095-4ca9-ad9f-e384590e6d27",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5e40a8f5-29bf-4a8d-bb12-2f541ab8a364"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "661107c3-941f-48f0-80d2-f2609f7d7a07",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "661107c3-941f-48f0-80d2-f2609f7d7a07",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5e40a8f5-29bf-4a8d-bb12-2f541ab8a364"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7209e092-7571-488a-a754-bca52da5cb33",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 2.\n- **Level #1:** Students review how to reduce AI hallucinations.\n- **Level #2:** Students complete a formative assessment.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7209e092-7571-488a-a754-bca52da5cb33",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5e40a8f5-29bf-4a8d-bb12-2f541ab8a364"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8a23a841-5613-4a65-8755-cfa363de1813",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Observe students as they complete the assessment. Look for signs that they understand AI hallucinations and how to counter them. Note if students struggle to connect fact-checking techniques to real-world examples.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use student responses to assess how well they grasp the risks of AI hallucinations and the strategies to counter them. Teachers can determine next steps based on common student responses:\n- If students identify hallucinations but struggle to explain their impact:\n   - Have students revisit the Hallucination Case Studies slide and discuss their notes in small groups.\n   - Ask: \"Why does AI misinformation matter in real-world settings?\"\n- If students don't apply fact-checking strategies:\n   - Direct them to the Reduce AI Hallucinations slide and have them match each strategy (careful prompting, skepticism, fact-checking) to a real-world example.\n   - Ask: “Which strategy would help verify this AI-generated claim?”\n- If students effectively explain AI hallucinations, impacts, and fact-checking strategies:\n   - Move on to the wrap-up discussion.\n   - Have students share how they would explain AI hallucinations to someone unfamiliar with them.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8a23a841-5613-4a65-8755-cfa363de1813",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5e40a8f5-29bf-4a8d-bb12-2f541ab8a364"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6e72c307-f3dc-4f44-a68b-68ad5f0b2a10",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:**Engage students in critical thinking about AI hallucinations.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to take a minute to write a response to the Question of the Day in their Unit Guide. Encourage them to use specific examples from the lesson, such as case studies or AI-generated errors they encountered.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Question of the Day can be used as a formative assessment to check whether students can recall real-world examples of AI hallucinations and their impacts. If students struggle to provide examples, review key moments from the lesson, such as the case studies and AI panel discussion."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6e72c307-f3dc-4f44-a68b-68ad5f0b2a10",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f1843622-db5f-4fdf-a6a2-a359f3c26e4c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "79f557e6-4b54-4a29-a19c-d3c6b94b680f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "79f557e6-4b54-4a29-a19c-d3c6b94b680f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f1843622-db5f-4fdf-a6a2-a359f3c26e4c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5e10ecc5-902c-41ea-96f7-335f61ff2812",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that students will respond to statements about AI hallucinations by standing up if they agree or staying seated if they disagree. Emphasize that there are no right or wrong answers—the goal is to encourage reasoning and discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read each statement aloud. Pause after each statement and let students vote by standing or sitting. Ask a standing student and a seated student to share their reasoning. Use the follow-up prompts:\n- *What makes hallucinations easy or hard to spot?*\n- *Can you think of a real-world example where an AI hallucination was helpful or harmful?*\n- *What factors make AI hallucinations dangerous in some cases but not others?*\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students all agree on a statement, challenge them by asking: \"Can you argue the other side?\" or \"What might change your perspective?\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5e10ecc5-902c-41ea-96f7-335f61ff2812",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f1843622-db5f-4fdf-a6a2-a359f3c26e4c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "14ceb3be-6717-47cf-b5fa-d1443e9d01a4",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "14ceb3be-6717-47cf-b5fa-d1443e9d01a4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f1843622-db5f-4fdf-a6a2-a359f3c26e4c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "233cc346-50b4-434e-adcf-bc0ff1bb1111",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Level 3 to complete the End of Lesson Survey.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "233cc346-50b4-434e-adcf-bc0ff1bb1111",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f1843622-db5f-4fdf-a6a2-a359f3c26e4c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e84a29f3-2e96-488a-8f34-6690527db07c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** To introduce an interesting new career that is related to the work that students will be asked to do today– refining prompts in order to produce high-quality AI output.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the \"AI's Hottest New Job Pays Up to $250K a Year. So I Applied\" video.\n\n**Questions to consider with the video:**\n- *What does a prompt engineer do?*\n- *What skills do you need to have to be a prompt engineer?*\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to explain that a prompt engineer is someone who develops prompts to get the best output from a large language model. A prompt engineer needs to be good at writing clearly and giving good instructions. They should know how to translate between a machine and a human.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *prompt engineering*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day.\n",
        "name": "What is a Prompt Engineer?"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e84a29f3-2e96-488a-8f34-6690527db07c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ac3e8d53-c569-4880-a934-6138a05cd766"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c38f45d4-95c4-41cd-b0e5-3a592c257797",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Provide students with a structured method to improve AI-generated responses using five key elements of a strong prompt. They will have a chance to test out each method as they work through levels.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the key elements of a prompt. Explain that just like giving instructions to a friend, the more details you provide, the better the response. By specifying what we want AI to do, giving context, and even suggesting a format, we can make AI's responses much more useful.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce \"TaCo FoRT\" as a mnemonic: Task, Context, Format, Reference, Tone.\n",
        "duration": "25",
        "name": "AI Prompting Framework",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Suggest that students remember \"TaCo FoRT\" so they can systematically check if they've included each element in their prompts. This prompting framework can be used in future interactions with AI Chatbots in this lesson and beyond."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c38f45d4-95c4-41cd-b0e5-3a592c257797",
        "lesson_activity.key": "baf2eba5-43a3-47d5-bc94-6e7cb5645cb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f33cf96d-bf08-4eaa-bef5-59b38aaf6442",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f33cf96d-bf08-4eaa-bef5-59b38aaf6442",
        "lesson_activity.key": "baf2eba5-43a3-47d5-bc94-6e7cb5645cb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ffe21f54-8b26-4ad5-bad8-6bd8f87471b6",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Direct students to take out their Problem Solving with AI Unit Guide.****\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 1 to practice providing the core task or objective the AI needs to address. Students should complete the corresponding section of their Unit Guide.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ffe21f54-8b26-4ad5-bad8-6bd8f87471b6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "baf2eba5-43a3-47d5-bc94-6e7cb5645cb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1c66974c-f6cc-4cc8-abc6-3a19356b40af",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As you move around the room and engage students in thoughtful reflection by asking, \"How did AI's response change after you added context?\" or \"Did AI follow your requested format? Why or why not?\" or \"What's still missing from AI's response?\". Offer guidance if a prompt remains too vague (e.g., \"Make sure you tell the AI exactly what you want it to do!\").\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What task did you add to the original prompt?*\n- *How did refining the prompt improve AI's output?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** The aim is for students to recognize that making the Task explicit often leads to more focused and relevant AI replies. They should see how even small changes in wording can clarify the objective for the AI. This discussion should serve as an opportunity for guided practice before students work independently through the next four refining output activities.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 2 to complete Levels 2 through 5. Students should complete the corresponding sections of their Unit Guide.\n- **Level #2:** Students practice providing necessary background information to give context for the task.\n- **Level #3:** Students practice providing references, examples, or models to guide the AI.\n- **Level #4:** Students practice specifying the format in which the response should be delivered.\n- **Level #5:** Students practice setting the tone for the AI response.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1c66974c-f6cc-4cc8-abc6-3a19356b40af",
        "lesson_activity.key": "baf2eba5-43a3-47d5-bc94-6e7cb5645cb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2109e41e-e5ef-439b-91c0-6d78bfa422db",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As you move around the room and engage students in thoughtful reflection by asking, \"How did AI's response change after you added context?\" or \"Did AI follow your requested format? Why or why not?\" or \"What’s still missing from AI's response?\"\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2109e41e-e5ef-439b-91c0-6d78bfa422db",
        "lesson_activity.key": "baf2eba5-43a3-47d5-bc94-6e7cb5645cb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3c3b18dc-736f-4e2a-94d1-28a9379edac6",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to review the outcomes of debugging and refining output. Ensure students understand that every time they refine their prompt, they are debugging AI—just like a programmer debugs their code. The first response might be generic, but by adjusting details and testing different versions, they can generate clearer, more accurate AI outputs.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3c3b18dc-736f-4e2a-94d1-28a9379edac6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "baf2eba5-43a3-47d5-bc94-6e7cb5645cb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "785b9e67-a936-4f6c-a8f2-eb08e48d516d",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:** Students refine a generic prompt using the Prompting Framework to improve accuracy.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 6 to complete Levels 6 through 8.\n- **Level #6:** This panel level serves as a review of the key elements of prompt refinement.\n- **Level #7:** Students choose a generic prompt to improve. They use at least three elements (Task, Context, Reference, Format, Tone) and iterate on their prompt until they have one that consistently generates helpful AI output.\n- **Level #8:** Students copy their revised prompt from Level 7 into the free response level. Then they explain why their revised prompt led to a better result than the initial generic prompt.\n",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Check Your Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The assessment on Level 8 can be used as a formative assessment of the lesson objectives. As students submit their final revised prompts, circulate and provide quick feedback by:\n- Looking for clear, specific refinements that improved the AI's output.\n- Asking probing questions like:\n   - *\"What made the AI's response better after refining your prompt?\"*\n   - *\"How did adding context change the AI’s response?\"*\n   - *\"Why do you think AI initially struggled with this prompt?\"*\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "785b9e67-a936-4f6c-a8f2-eb08e48d516d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "baf2eba5-43a3-47d5-bc94-6e7cb5645cb2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d924b5ae-d80e-4280-8fa5-d2cd3c84017e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-bullseye-arrow\"></i> **Goal of this activity:**Students summarize their learning about AI prompt refinement in a concise, creative, and engaging way.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a sticky note.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to take a minute and answer the Question of the Day on a sticky note, providing a specific example of how one of the key element (Task, Context, Format, Reference, Tone) might be used to refine output.\n\nExample Student Responses:\n- **Format:** Write a poem, such as a haiku or limerick\n- **Tone:** Write in a professional tone, as if you are a college admissions counselor\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Prompt deeper thinking with a guiding question:*What strategies did you use in the levels? Give an example of how you added more context or chose a different tone.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students add their sticky notes to the classroom anchor chart.\n",
        "name": "Key Elements Anchor Chart",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use color-coded notes for different key elements to create a more structured visual representation. This classroom anchor chart will become useful for students to try new ways to refine their prompts throughout this unit and others in the CSAIF curriculum. Encourage students to add to the anchor chart whenever they have a new way of refining their prompts that leads to more interesting, accurate, and fair output."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Question of the Day can be used as a formative assessment of understanding the relationship between prompting techniques and improved AI-generated responses. Make sure students write their name on their sticky note if you plan to use it as an assessment."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d924b5ae-d80e-4280-8fa5-d2cd3c84017e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ffa4610c-70da-4aca-a26a-41064f628c2d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "eb96fce3-3072-4ac1-a527-34a95454703f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "eb96fce3-3072-4ac1-a527-34a95454703f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ffa4610c-70da-4aca-a26a-41064f628c2d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f74173c-d8f3-401f-aac2-73631a98a165",
